1 REGISTERED APPRENTICESHIP AFTER GRADUATING FROM DELMAR HIGH SCHOOL
2 IN DELMAR, DELAWARE; AND
3 B. IS A RESIDENT OF DELMAR, MARYLAND;
4 Subtitle 40. Fallen AND SURVIVING Transportation Workers Scholarship Program.
5 18–4001.
6 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
7 (B) “ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS:
8 (1) ACCEPTED FOR ADMISSION OR ENROLLED IN A REGULAR
9 UNDERGRADUATE, GRADUATE, OR PROFESSIONAL PROGRAM AT AN INSTITUTION OF
10 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION;
11 (2) AT LEAST 16 YEARS OLD; AND
12 (3) (I) A SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER;
13 (II) 1. A CHILD, STEPCHILD, SPOUSE, OR UNMARRIED
14 PARTNER OF A SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER; OR
15 2. IF A SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER DOES NOT
16 HAVE A CHILD, STEPCHILD, SPOUSE, OR UNMARRIED PARTNER, A SIBLING OF THE
17 SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER;
18 (III) 1. A SURVIVING CHILD, STEPCHILD, SPOUSE, OR
19 UNMARRIED PARTNER OF A FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER; OR
20 2. IF A FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER DOES NOT
21 HAVE A SURVIVING CHILD, STEPCHILD, SPOUSE, OR UNMARRIED PARTNER, A
22 SIBLING OF THE FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER; OR
23 (IV) A CHILD OR STEPCHILD OF AN UNMARRIED PARTNER.
24 [(b)] (C) “Fallen transportation worker” means an individual:
25 (1) Whose occupation is in the construction, rehabilitation, or operation of
26 a transportation facility or transportation facilities project in the State; and
27 (2) Who died, on or after January 1, 2022, as a result of an accident
28 occurring while the individual was performing any job duty necessary for the construction,

4 SENATE BILL 728
1 maintenance, rehabilitation, or operation of a transportation facility or transportation
2 facilities project in the State.
3 [(c)] (D) “Fund” means the Fallen AND SURVIVING Transportation Workers
4 Scholarship Fund.
5 [(d)] (E) “Program” means the Fallen AND SURVIVING Transportation Workers
6 Scholarship Program.
7 (F) “SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL:
8 (1) WHOSE OCCUPATION IS IN THE CONSTRUCTION,
9 REHABILITATION, OR OPERATION OF A TRANSPORTATION FACILITY OR
10 TRANSPORTATION FACILITIES PROJECT IN THE STATE; AND
11 (2) WHO SURVIVED, ON OR AFTER JANUARY 1, 2022, AN ACCIDENT:
12 (I) RESULTING IN AT LEAST $100,000,000 IN TOTAL DAMAGES
13 TO A TRANSPORTATION FACILITY OR TRANSPORTATION FACILITIES PROJECT IN THE
14 STATE; AND
15 (II) OCCURRING WHILE THE INDIVIDUAL WAS PERFORMING ANY
16 JOB DUTY NECESSARY FOR THE CONSTRUCTION, MAINTENANCE, REHABILITATION,
17 OR OPERATION OF A TRANSPORTATION FACILITY OR TRANSPORTATION FACILITIES
18 PROJECT IN THE STATE.
19 (G) “TRANSPORTATION FACILITIES PROJECT” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN
20 § 4–101 OF THE TRANSPORTATION ARTICLE.
21 [(e)] (H) “Transportation facility” has the meaning stated in § 3–101 of the
22 Transportation Article.
23 [(f) “Transportation facilities project” has the meaning stated in § 4–101 of the
24 Transportation Article.]
25 (I) “UNMARRIED PARTNER” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO:
26 (1) AT THE TIME OF A FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER’S DEATH:
27 (I) WAS IN A COMMITTED RELATIONSHIP WITH THE FALLEN
28 TRANSPORTATION WORKER; AND
29 (II) SHARED A PRIMARY RESIDENCE WITH THE FALLEN
30 TRANSPORTATION WORKER; OR AND

SENATE BILL 728 5
1 (III) WAS RECEIVING AND RELIED ON, IN WHOLE OR IN PART, THE
2 REASONABLE NECESSITIES OF LIFE FROM THE FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER;
3 OR
4 (2) AT THE TIME OF A SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKER’S
5 ACCIDENT:
6 (I) WAS IN A COMMITTED RELATIONSHIP WITH THE SURVIVING
7 TRANSPORTATION WORKER; AND
8 (II) SHARED A PRIMARY RESIDENCE WITH THE SURVIVING
9 TRANSPORTATION WORKER; AND
10 (III) WAS RECEIVING AND RELIED ON, IN WHOLE OR IN PART, THE
11 REASONABLE NECESSITIES OF LIFE FROM THE SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION
12 WORKER.
13 18–4002.
14 (a) There is a Fallen AND SURVIVING Transportation Workers Scholarship
15 Program.
16 (b) The purpose of the Program is to provide tuition assistance to a student who
17 was [a dependent or is the surviving spouse of a fallen transportation worker] IMPACTED
18 BY AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A FALLEN TRANSPORTATION WORKER OR A SURVIVING
19 TRANSPORTATION WORKER.
20 18–4003.
21 (a) An individual may apply to an eligible institution of postsecondary education
22 for a scholarship under this subtitle if the individual is[:
23 (1) Accepted for admission or enrolled in a regular undergraduate,
24 graduate, or professional program at an institution of postsecondary education;
25 (2) At least 16 years old; and
26 (3) The child, stepchild, or surviving spouse of a fallen transportation
27 worker] AN ELIGIBLE RECIPIENT OF A SCHOLARSHIP UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
28 (b) A scholarship awarded under this subtitle:
29 (1) May be used for the [tuition and mandatory fees] TOTAL COST OF
30 ATTENDANCE at any institution of postsecondary education; and

6 SENATE BILL 728
1 (2) May not:
2 (i) Exceed the equivalent annual tuition and mandatory fees of an
3 undergraduate student at the 4–year institution of higher education within the University
4 System of Maryland, other than the University of Maryland Global Campus and the
5 University of Maryland, Baltimore Campus, with the highest annual expenses for a
6 full–time undergraduate; and
7 (ii) Be less than the lesser of:
8 1. $3,000; or
9 2. The equivalent tuition and mandatory fees of the
10 institution attended by the recipient of the scholarship.
11 (c) (1) Each institution of postsecondary education shall determine eligibility
12 of individuals who apply to the institution for the Program.
13 (2) Subject to the availability of funds, funds for the Program shall be
14 allocated by the Commission to each institution of postsecondary education based on the
15 number of eligible recipients attending each institution.
16 (3) In February and October each year, beginning in 2024, each institution
17 of postsecondary education shall report to the Commission the number of eligible recipients
18 attending the institution.
19 (4) The Commission shall allocate funds for awards to institutions of
20 postsecondary education on verification of eligible recipients attending the institutions.
21 (5) If funds cannot be allocated in the fiscal year in which awards are made,
22 priority shall be given to allocating funds for those awards in the immediately following
23 fiscal year.
24 (d) Each recipient of a scholarship under this subtitle may hold the award for 5
25 years of full–time study or 8 years of part–time study.
26 (e) To the extent practicable, the Department of Transportation, a local
27 department of transportation, or a contractor that employed fallen transportation workers
28 OR SURVIVING TRANSPORTATION WORKERS shall provide to the Commission the names
29 and contact information for the families of the fallen transportation workers OR SURVIVING
30 TRANSPORTATION WORKERS AFTER ANY ACCIDENT RESULTING IN ELIGIBILITY FOR
31 A SCHOLARSHIP UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
32 18–4004.
33 (a) There is a Fallen AND SURVIVING Transportation Workers Scholarship Fund.

SENATE BILL 728 7
1 (b) The Commission shall administer the Fund.
2 (c) (1) The Fund is a special, nonlapsing fund that is not subject to § 7–302 of
3 the State Finance and Procurement Article.
4 (2) The State Treasurer shall hold the Fund separately, and the
5 Comptroller shall account for the Fund.
6 (d) The Fund consists of:
7 (1) Money appropriated in the State budget to the Fund;
8 (2) Interest earnings; and
9 (3) Any other money from any other source accepted by the Commission for
10 the benefit of the Fund.
11 (e) The Fund may be used only to award scholarships under the Program.
12 (f) (1) The State Treasurer shall invest the money of the Fund in the same
13 manner as other State money may be invested.
14 (2) Any interest earnings of the Fund shall be credited to the Fund.
15 (g) Expenditures from the Fund may be made only in accordance with the State
16 budget.
17 (h) The Commission:
18 (1) May accept any gift or grant from any person for the Fund; and
19 (2) Shall deposit any gift or grant that it receives for the Program with the
20 State Treasurer.
21 (i) Funding for the Program shall be as provided in the State budget.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
23 1, 2026.

